Note.En: Assumption of the credit line is reported

The FI has reached an agreement with the customer for a repayment plan which allows the partial resolution of a previous delinquency situation characterized by the presence of overdue or unpaid installments

Faced with missing payments, the FI is evaluating the possibility of delinquency and is carrying out an attempt to gain payment from co-borrowers, the outcome of which is not yet known. On the other hand, where there is a payment and/or and agreement between the FI and the data subject, the status in the next contribution will be Blank.
A court injunction was issued due to overdue and unpaid installments.
A notice of foreclosure was issued.
A bankruptcy request was made (for companies and sole proprietorships).
The account is removed and leads to financial loss; with this status closure is also expected. CRIF does not expect any further communication.

After repeated defaults, the account becomes delinquent. In the case of a positive outcome the status becomes U (re-establishment of positive payment behavior); in the case of persistence or worsening of the default status, in general the credit is transferred (C) or written off (P).
Credit is transferred to a debt collection company; the FI removes the credit relationship. CRIF does not expect any further communication.

Note.En: This status applies to the case in which a customer suddenly decides to abandon a relationship early with the bank or in the case in which the natural expiry is not renewed. For example, the customer decides to abandon all their credit cards on their expiry and not to renew them

The FI reports this status whenever a customer disputes a debit. This is confirmed when the customer communicates their intention NOT to carry out the payment, which results in errors in the debit. For example, the reference subject does not recognize some operations which were debited or disputes the accuracy of some debits.

This status occurs when the FI decides to close the credit relationship following delinquency. For example, the customer has accumulated defaults so high that the FI decides to close the credit relationship.
